#sent_text:The productions of Tallis, Birde, Morley, and Farrant, of Gibbons and Child, of Blow and Purcell, of Croft, Greene, Boyce, Nares, and we might add others, are not only excellent qguoad compositions, but equally perfect as forming a part of our religious worship: they never for a moment lose the true devotional character, though their difference from each other, in many respects, is as wide as the several periods at which they were written.

#sent_text:John Bull would be a fitting name, in truth, for the composer of the English National Anthem ; the validity of the assignment, however, is stronger with reference to the people who have adopted the tune in one form and altered it into another to please themselves, than to the learned musician who composed a piece with the same number of bars.
